TWO people were killed in a crash involving a Tesla Model S. According to cops, no one was in the driver’s seat at the time of the crash in Carlton Woods, near The Woodlands in Houston, Texas, on 17 April. The electric car immediately burst into flames on impact. According to Carscoops, Constable Mark Herman from the Harris County Precinct said he found bodies in the front passenger seat of the car and the rear, but no one in the driver’s seat. Two men dead after fiery crash in Tesla Model S.“[Investigators] are 100-percent certain that no one was in the driver seat driving that vehicle at the time of impact,” Harris County Precinct 4 Constable Mark Herman said. “They are positive.” #KHOU11 https://t.co/q57qfIXT4f pic.twitter.com/eQMwpSMLt2  Speaking to KPRC 2, the brother-in-law of one of the men killed in the crash said he was taking the car for a spin with his best friend and they were the only two in the vehicle. The car crashed down the road with the owner in the back seat, indicating he was showing off the car’s Autopilot semi-autonomous driving system.  Constables said the Model S was travelling at high speed when it ran off the road and slammed into a tree. Both passengers were pronounced dead at the scene.